---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="Linear Projections Change Representation Size">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L09" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What is a linear projection?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        A linear projection is a matrix multiply with a learned weight matrix. It can change the width of your vectors, or keep it the same.
        If your hidden state has dimension 2048 and you need a query vector of dimension 256,
        you multiply by a learned weight matrix that maps [2048] to [256].
      </p>
      <p>
        The weight matrix is learned during training. It decides which combinations of input features matter for the output. You do not need to understand the learning — just that the projection is a matrix multiply with a specific shape contract.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the bridge from linear algebra to transformer semantics. The same hidden state can be projected into different spaces with different learned matrices. That is why one input vector can become a query, a key, a value, or an FFN-expanded representation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Projecting from d_model=4 to d_q=2:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); line-height: 1.7;">
          hidden = [2, -1, 3, 0]
          <br />
          W_q =
          <br />
          [[1, 0],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[0, 1],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[1, -1],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[0, 2]]
          <br />
          hidden &times; W_q = [5, -4]
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          Each output coordinate is a weighted sum of the input coordinates. The projection does not just shrink width; it mixes features into a new basis.
        </p>
        <div style="border-top: var(--border-subtle); margin-top: var(--space-3); padding-top: var(--space-3); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          W_k =
          <br />
          [[0, 1],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[1, 0],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[-1, 2],
          <br />
          &nbsp;[1, 0]]
          <br />
          hidden &times; W_k = [-4, 8]
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          Same input, different learned matrix, different output space. That is the key idea behind Q/K/V: the role changes because the projection changes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Projection: X [n_tokens, d_in] &times; W [d_in, d_out] = Y [n_tokens, d_out]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Common uses in LLMs:</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Q projection: [n, d_model] &times; [d_model, d_q] &rarr; [n, d_q]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-token);">Output head: [n, d_model] &times; [d_model, |V|] &rarr; [n, |V|]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">FFN up-projection: [n, d_model] &times; [d_model, d_ff] &rarr; [n, d_ff]</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-token);">Y = X W</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">where W is a learned weight matrix of shape [d_in, d_out]</div>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
        Read the columns of <code>W</code> as output features. Each column tells you how to combine the input coordinates to produce one output coordinate.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Every Q, K, V, output, and FFN layer in a transformer uses projections.
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, each projection is a <code>ggml_mul_mat</code> call with a stored weight tensor.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          This is why transformer code can look repetitive: same operation family, different tensors, different semantic role.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Projection cost is n_tokens &times; d_in &times; d_out multiply-adds. For large models, d_ff can be 4&times; d_model or more, making FFN projections the most expensive operations per layer.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          This also explains why prefill and decode feel different: in prefill, many token rows are multiplied at once; in decode, one row is multiplied by many large matrices repeatedly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L09"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L09-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'If hidden states have shape [10, 512] and W_q has shape [512, 64], what is the Q shape?',
            tag: 'shape',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: '[10, 64]', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: '[512, 64]', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: '[10, 512]', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: '[10, 512] × [512, 64] → [10, 64]. Each of the 10 tokens gets a 64-dimensional query vector.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L09-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why can the same hidden state produce both Q and K vectors?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Because it is multiplied by different learned weight matrices', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Because Q and K are copied from different halves of the same vector', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Because one comes from attention and one from the tokenizer', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The input hidden state is the same, but different learned matrices define different output spaces. That is why Q, K, and V can serve different roles.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
